\pagenumbering{arabic}
\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}

The nature of the early Universe still holds many mysteries, though particle physicists and cosmologists have together constructed many theories which could help unravel them. One such conundrum is baryogenesis: The hypothesised process through which the Universe has come to be matter dominated. Since matter and antimatter annihilate, the only way for the Universe to exist in either form is if at some instance there was an asymmetry between them. Andrei Sakharov produced a set of restrictions on any possible solutions to this problem in 1967 whereby he suggested that if the Universe had at some point been out of thermal equilibrium and processes which violated charge (\(C\)), charge-parity (\(CP\)) and baryon number (\(B\)) had occurred, it would be possible for this asymmetry between matter and antimatter to arise \cite{sak}. Since the proposal of these Standard Model (SM) breaking Sakharov conditions, we have discovered that neutrinos have mass which indicates that another symmetry, \((B-L)\),  must have also been broken \cite{nnbarOsc}.\\

In order to determine if these properties were violated, it is necessary to hypothesise and investigate a process which goes Beyond the Standard Model (BSM). Baryogenesis could be explained if we were to observe the oscillation of baryonic matter via the mixing of a quark to its antiparticle. This process would also indicate that the matter which makes up our Universe is less stable than we think. \(\nnbar\) oscillations are an entirely theorised, BSM process which would violate \(B\) and \((B-L)\) by \(\Delta B = \Delta (B-L) = 2\) and would therefore help deepen our understanding of the BSM processes which could provide this explanation \cite{nnbarTheory}.\\

BSM processes such as \(\nnbar\) oscillations are extremely rare. The Super Kamiokande collaboration proposed an estimated lower-limit on the lifetime of a neutron to be \(\sim 10^{32}\) years \cite{superK}. (Please note: This lifetime is not a fixed value and is used only for the purpose of making event rate estimates.) In order to conquer this issue, neutrino detectors with capacities in the tens of kilotonnes will be used to try and observe the oscillations, since they could potentially reduce the necessary exposure time to a matter of months.\\

Long and short baseline experiments have been setup across the world in order to investigate the nature of neutrinos. Liquid argon is one of the leading detector materials since its high resolution provides outstanding signal distinction \cite{LArProperties}. Equation~(\ref{eq:nuAr}) describes the interaction which occurs between an argon nucleus and and electron neutrino \cite{GLoBES}.

\begin{equation}\label{eq:nuAr}
 \nu_e + ^{40}\mbox{Ar} \rightarrow e^- + ^{40}\mbox{K}^*
\end{equation}

There are already a handful of LArTPC experiments, such as MicroBooNE, which are up and running, however these are not on a scale large enough to detect an event as rare as the \(\nnbar\) oscillation. That being said, these detectors can be used to test reconstruction algorithms on events with similar topologies such as low-energy cosmogenic \(\bar{p}\) or \(\bar{n}\) annihilation on argon nuclei. In both cases, the low-energy antimatter will annihilate with its nearby matter component within the argon nucleus. \\

This research project aims to use Monte Carlo simulations of cosmogenic antimatter and \(\nnbar\) oscillation events to aid in the formulation of event reconstruction algorithms. These simulations provide particle samples in both the reconstructed form, which mimics exactly how the event would occur in the detector, and in the truth form, which contains exact information at a raw level. A comparison between the sample types would be used to calculate the efficiency and purity of the reconstruction algorithms with the overall intention of obtaining an estimate of DUNE's sensitivity to bound neutron-antineutron oscillations. \\

\clearpage
%---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{The LArTPC configuration}
\label{sec:uboone}

A liquid argon time projection chamber (LArTPC) utilises the dense nature and low cost of liquid argon by housing large fiducial volumes of it in a cuboid-shaped vessel \cite{uBooNETech}. A diagram of the structure of a general TPC is shown in Figure~\ref{fig:uBooNE}, in summary  \cite{uBoone}: 
\begin{itemize}
    \item A potential difference between then cathode and anode planes produce an electric field across the whole structure
    \begin{itemize}
        \item This field causes the negatively charged electrons to drift away from the cathode
    \end{itemize}
    \item On the opposite wall, there are 3 wire planes (U,V,Y) oriented at 60\(^o\)s to one another
    \begin{itemize}
        \item These wires log the electron's position and energy in the y-z planes
        \item A time projection of the drift electrons is used to obtain x-axis information
        \item Interaction vertices can be determined from this data
    \end{itemize}
    \item Behind the wire planes lies an array of photomultiplier tubes (PMTs)
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Incoming photons are analysed here 
    \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\begin{figure}[htb!]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[scale=1.1]{LArTPC.pdf}
    \caption{The LArTPC is visualised here, it can be seen that the 3 wire planes (usually labelled U, V and Y) lie on the same wall as the PMTs and are on the opposite wall to the cathode plane. An example track is shown along with the resulting ionization electrons and their drift direction. In this Figure, the x axis is positive in the electron drift direction.}
    \label{fig:uBooNE}
\end{figure}

When a neutrino interacts with the argon nuclei in the TPC, electrons are produced in accordance with the interaction in~\ref{eq:nuAr} and it is likely that they will undergo further interactions such as scattering and the emission of a photon off another argon nucleus. Eventually, any emitted photons will likely undergo pair production and subsequently cascade into an EM shower. Electrons or positrons in this shower may ionize the argon and the cathode causes the ionization electrons to drift across the TPC volume. Upon reaching the wire planes at a known position and with a calculable energy, the electron can be analysed to extract properties such as the energy and position of the ionization vertex. Similarly, photons can be analysed if they are picked up by any one of the PMTs. Track and shower objects are built up by locating all of the ionization electrons in an event. The electrons surrounding the track in Figure~\ref{fig:uBooNE} give an idea of how this is done \cite{uBoone}.\\

A Feynmann diagram of the process described by equation~(\ref{eq:nuAr}) is given in Figure~\ref{fig:FeynAr}. An example of how pair production may occur in the TPC is given by Figure~\ref{fig:PairProd}.

\begin{figure}[htb!]
    \begin{center}
        \begin{tikzpicture}
          \begin{feynman}
            \vertex (a1) {\(\nu_e\)};
            \vertex[below=1.5em of a1] (a2);
            \vertex[right=2.5cm of a2] (a3);
            \vertex[right=5cm of a1] (a4) {\(e^-\)};
        
            \vertex[below=6em of a1] (b1) {\(d\)};
            \vertex[above=1.5em of b1] (b2);
            \vertex[right=2.5cm of b2] (b3);
            \vertex[right=5cm of b1] (b4) {\(u\)};
            
            \vertex[below=1.5em of b1] (c1) {\(u\)};
            \vertex[right=5cm of c1] (c2) {\(u\)};
            
            \vertex[below=1.5em of c1] (d1) {\(d\)};
            \vertex[right=5cm of d1] (d2) {\(d\)};
        
            \diagram* {
              {[edges=fermion]
                (c1) -- (c2),
                (d1) -- (d2),
              },
                (a1) -- [fermion] (a3) -- [fermion] (a4),
                (a3) -- [scalar, edge label=\(W^-\)] (b3),
                (b1) -- [fermion] (b3) -- [fermion] (b4),
            };
        
            \draw [decoration={brace}, decorate] (d1.south west) -- (b1.north west)
                  node [pos=0.5, left] {\(n\)};
            \draw [decoration={brace}, decorate] (b4.north east) -- (d2.south east)
                  node [pos=0.5, right] {\(p\)};
          \end{feynman}
        \end{tikzpicture}
        \caption{When a \(\nu_{\mbox{\footnotesize e}}\) enters the TPC and interacts with the LAr, an electron is produced alongside the excited state of the argon atom, with photons being emitted to account for the energy loss and eventual de-excitation of the \(^{40}K^*\) nucleus.}
        \label{fig:FeynAr}
    \end{center}
\end{figure}

\begin{figure}[htb!]
\centering
\includegraphics[scale=0.8]{pairProduction.pdf}
\caption{An electron which interacts with a nucleus producing a photon as it is scattered, pair production then occurs during which a photon becomes an \(e^+e^-\) pair, the initial electron continues before potentially scattering again. At any point during the shower, \(e^+\)s or \(e^-\)s may ionize the argon and send drift electrons to the TPC.}
\label{fig:PairProd}
\end{figure}

In detectors such as MicroBooNE and DUNE, neutrinos will be produced by beams made at long and short baselines from the detector locations. MicroBooNE is a \(\sim\)60 tonne LArTPC and DUNE will contain \(\sim\)40 kilotonnes of liquid argon. Although the beam-lines will be the primary particle sources for each experiment, many other particle interactions may occur within the active volumes of the TPCs. For instance, MicroBooNE resides above the Earth, leaving it exposed to both atmospheric neutrinos and cosmogenic particles. In contrast, DUNE will be built underground so that the overburden of the Earth can shield the TPC from cosmic rays, though atmospheric neutrinos will still reach the detector. These particles and their interactions within the TPC will cause issues when it comes to event reconstruction. The first event seen by the MicroBooNE is given in Figure~\ref{fig:event} \cite{FermiToday} to give an idea of what is seen in an LArTPC.\\

Prior to the construction of LArTPC experiments, searches for \(\nnbar\) oscillations have been undertaken all over the world. For the most part, the lack of success in these previous attempts has been put down to the heavy overlay of atmospheric neutrino backgrounds. The resolution of these liquid argon-based experiments promises to dramatically reduce these effects, and therefore provide the greatest chance of successfully observing them \cite{nnbarPaper}. 

\begin{figure}[htb!]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{uBooNEevent.pdf}
\caption{The first event seen by MicroBooNE in October 2015. The various lines are particle tracks in the event.}
\label{fig:event}
\end{figure}

